Definition 2.13. Let $P\in\mathcal{P}$ be a poset and $G=(V,E)\in\mathcal{G}$ a graph, let us denote by $G\in\mathcal{S}$ the corresponding one dimensional simplicial complex. A $P-weighted\,\,graph$ is a pair $(G,\omega),$ where $\omega:(G,\subseteq)\to P$ is a morphism of posets i.e. a function $G\to P,$ which is continuous in the Alexandrov topology.
Definition 4.3. Let $G\in\mathcal{G}$ be a graph. We now define as the homology space of $G$, $H_{i}(G):=H_{i}(\mathrm{Cl}(G))$ .
Definition 2.8. A reflexive graph is a pair $G=(V,E)$, where $V$ is a finite set whose elements are called vertices and $E=\Delta_{V\times V}\cup E^{\prime}$ with $E^{\prime}\subseteq{V\choose 2}$, i.e. is a graph which has an edge (called self-loop) $(v,v)$ for every vertex $v\in V$. Equivalently, reflexive graphs can be seen as one dimensional simplicial complexes, identifying self-loops and vertices with $0$-simplices and edges with $1$-simplices. We will denote by $\mathcal{G}$ the category with objects reflexive graphs and morphisms the simplicial maps defined via the given identification with one dimensional simplicial complexes.
Definition 2.2. Let $P$ be a poset and $\mathcal{A}$ an arbitrary category. A $P$-persistent object in $\mathcal{A}$ is a functor $\varphi:P\to\mathcal{A}.$ $P$-persistent objects in $\mathcal{A}$ with their natural transformation form a category, which we will denote, as usual, by ${{\mathcal{A}}^{P}}.$ Given two categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B},$ to any functor $\phi:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ it corresponds a functor $\mathcal{A}^{P}\to\mathcal{B}^{P}$. It is given by $\varphi\in\mathcal{A}^{P}\mapsto\phi\circ\varphi$. It will be denoted by $\phi^{P}.$
Definition 2.1. A partially ordered set, briefly a poset, is a pair $P=(P,\leq)$, where $P$ is a set and $\leq$ is an order relation on it, i.e. a reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive relation on $P.$ Posets form a category, denoted by $\mathcal{P}$, where morphisms are the order preserving functions. In this paper we will consider only finite posets.
Definition 3.11. Let $\tau\in\mathcal{T}_{f}^{P}$, the composition $\mathrm{H}^{\mathrm{S}}_{i}\circ\tau\in\mathrm{Vect}_{k}^{P}$ will be called the $i^{\mathrm{th}}$ $P$-persistent homology of $\tau\in\mathcal{T}_{f}^{P}$.
Definition 2.10. Given a simplicial complex $\Sigma$ there is a functor $k_{1}:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{G}$ where $k_{1}(\Sigma)$ is the (reflexive) graph corresponding to the $1-$skeleton of $\Sigma$.
Definition 4.7. Let $X,Y\in\mathcal{T}_{f}$, and let $\pi_{n}(X,x)$ denote the homotopy group of the space $X$ at base point $x\in X$. A map $f:X\to Y$ is a weak homotopy equivalence if the following condition are both verified: 1. $f$ induces an isomorphism of the connected components of $X$ and $Y$ $\Pi_{0}(f):\Pi_{0}(X)\to\Pi_{0}(Y)$ 2. for all $x\in X$, and $n\geq 1$ is an isomorphism on the homotopy groups $\pi_{n}(f):\pi_{n}(X,x)\to\pi_{n}(Y,f(x))$
Definition 3.3. Let $\bar{\mathcal{G}}_{P}$ be the subcategory of $\mathcal{G}_{P}$ with the same objects, and morphisms the maps $\alpha:(C,\omega)\to(D,\omega^{\prime})$ such that for every $x\in G$, $\omega^{\prime}(\alpha(x))=\omega(x)$. We set $\bar{\Phi}_{P}$ as the restriction of $\Phi_{P}$ to $\bar{\mathcal{G}}_{P}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $(X,d)$ be a $V$-space and $\epsilon\in V$ with $\epsilon\succ 0$. $B_{\epsilon}(x)=\{y\in X\mid d(y,x)\prec\epsilon\}$ is the open ball with radius $\epsilon$ about the point $x\in X$.
Definition 3.2. A value distributive lattice is a completely distributive lattice $L$ for which $L_{\prec}=\{a\in L\mid a\succ 0\}$ forms a filter.
Definition 3.7. Let $(X,V,d)$ be any continuity space and $(x_{i})_{i\in I}$ be any net in $X$. We say that $(x_{n})$ $d$-converges to a point $x\in X$ whenever for all $\epsilon\succ 0$ there exists $i_{0}\in I$ so that for all $i\geq i_{0}$, $x_{i}\in B_{\epsilon}(x)$.
Definition IV.5. Let $\rho(w_{i})$ be a meaning state $I\to\tilde{M}Q(p_{i})$ corresponding to word $w_{i}$ with type $p_{i}$ in a sentence $w_{1}\ldots w_{n}$. Given a type-reduction $\alpha:p_{1}\cdot\ldots\cdot p_{n}\to s$, the meaning of the sentence is defined as: $\rho(w_{1}\ldots w_{n}):=\tilde{M}Q(\alpha)\big{(}\rho(w_{1})\otimes_{\mathbf{% CPM}}\ldots\otimes_{\mathbf{CPM}}\rho(w_{n})\big{)}$
Definition V.1. For every object $A$ of $D(\mathcal{C})$, the morphisms of $D(\mathcal{C})$, $\mu:A\otimes_{\mathbf{D}}A\rightarrow A$ defined by the following diagram in $\mathcal{C}$: and $\iota:I\rightarrow A$ with the following definition in $\mathcal{C}$: are the multiplication and unit of a $\dagger$-Frobenius algebra $\mathcal{F}_{\mathbf{D}}$—where $\sigma$ is the natural swap isomorphism in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition IV.3. A morphism $f:A\rightarrow B$ of $\mathbf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ is completely positive if there exists an object $C$ and a morphism $k:C\otimes A\rightarrow B$, in $\mathcal{C}$, such that $f$ embeds in $\mathcal{C}$ as $(k\otimes k_{*})\circ(1_{A}\otimes\eta_{C^{*}}\otimes 1_{A^{*}})$ or, pictorially,
Definition II.1. Let $|w_{i}\rangle$ be a vector $I\to Q(p_{i})$ corresponding to word $w_{i}$ with type $p_{i}$ in a sentence $w_{1}w_{2}\ldots w_{n}$. Given a type-reduction $\alpha:p_{1}\cdot p_{2}\cdot\ldots\cdot p_{n}\to s$, the meaning of the sentence is defined as: $|w_{1}w_{2}\ldots w_{n}\rangle:=Q(\alpha)(|w_{1}\rangle\otimes\ldots\otimes|w_% {n}\rangle)$
Definition IV.2. The category $\mathbf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ with • the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$; • morphisms between objects $A$ and $B$ of $\mathbf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ are morphisms $A\otimes A^{*}\rightarrow B\otimes B^{*}$ of $\mathcal{C}$. • composition and dagger are inherited from $\mathcal{C}$ via the embedding $E:\mathbf{D}(\mathcal{C})\hookrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ defined by $\left\{\begin{array}[]{rll}A&\mapsto A\otimes A^{*}&\text{on objects};\\ f&\mapsto f&\text{on morphisms}.\end{array}\right.$
Definition IV.4. The category $\mathbf{CPM}(\mathcal{C})$ is the subcategory of $\mathbf{D}(\mathcal{C})$ whose objects are the same and morphisms are completely positive maps.
Definition IV.1. Let a distributional model be given in the form of a Hilbert space $M$, in which every word $w_{t}$ is represented by a statistical ensemble $\{(p_{i},|w_{t}^{i}\rangle)\}_{i}$—where $|w_{t}^{i}\rangle$ is a vector corresponding to a specific unambiguous meaning of the word that can occur with probability $p_{i}$. The distributional meaning of the word is defined as: $\rho(w_{t})=\sum_{i}p_{i}|w_{t}^{i}\rangle\langle w_{t}^{i}|$
Definition 3.3. We call an object $C$ of a topos $\bf E$ weakly contractible, if any epimorphism $D\to C$ splits in $\bf E$, i.e. if there is a morphism $C\to D$ such that the composition $C\to D\to C$ is the identity. We say that a topos $\bf E$ has enough weakly contractible objects if for any object $C$ of $\bf E$ there is an epimorphism $D\to C$ with $D$ weakly contractible.
Definition 3.1. We say that $\bf E$ is $\alpha$-transfinite if for any ordinal $\lambda\leq\alpha$ and for any $\lambda$-tower $(E_{i})_{i<\lambda}$ of epimorphisms, i.e. with $E_{i+1}\to E_{i}$ an epimorphism for all $1\leq i+1<\lambda$, the transfinite composition $E_{<\lambda}=\lim_{i<\lambda}E_{i}\to E_{0}$ is an epimorphism. We say that $\bf E$ is transfinite if it is $\alpha$-transfinite for all cardinals $\alpha$.
Definition 5.2. Let $\alpha$ be an infinite cardinal. We say that a site $\bf C$ is $\alpha$-small if for any object $C$ in $\bf C$ there is a set of covering morphisms $K(C)$ of $C$ with $\operatorname{card}K(C)\leq\alpha$ such that for any covering morphism $E\to C$ in $\bf C$ there is $D\to C$ in $K(C)$ and a factorization $D\to E\to C$.
Definition 3.6. A coherent site $\bf C$ is called admissible if its topology is subcanonical and for a finite family of objects $(C_{i})_{i\in I}$ the coproduct $C=\coprod_{i\in I}C_{i}$ exists and $\{C_{i}\to C\ |\ i\in I\}$ is a covering. We furthermore assume that in ${\mathbf{C}}$ there is a strict initial object and coproducts are disjoint and stable under pullback, see [12, App.] and Definition 7.3.
Definition 6.1. A morphism $f:V\to U$ in ${{\rm pro}^{\alpha}\operatorname{-}}\bf C$ is a pro-covering morphism if $f$ has a level representation by covering morphisms in $\bf C$.
Definition 3.9. An admissible site $\bf C$ is called $\alpha$-transfinite if $\alpha$-limits exist in ${\mathbf{C}}$ and if transfinite compositions of $\lambda$-towers of covering morphisms ($\lambda\leq\alpha$) are covering morphisms, i.e. we assume that for a $\lambda$-tower $(F_{i})_{i<\lambda}$ in $\bf C$ with $F_{i+1}\to F_{i}$ a covering morphism for all $i+1<\lambda$ that $F_{<\lambda}\to F_{0}$ is a covering morphism.
Definition 7.3. We call a small category ${\mathbf{D}}$ a dc-category if finite coproducts exist in ${\mathbf{D}}$ and furthermore finite coproducts are disjoint and stable under pullback, see [12, App.]. The finite coverings of the form $\{V_{i}\to V\ |\ i\in I\}$ with $V=\coprod_{i\in I}V_{i}$ define a basis for a topology on ${\mathbf{D}}$, which we call the dc-topology.
Definition 0.2.4. Let $X$ be a set, and ${\mathcal{C}}$ a small category. A presheaf structure on $X$ consists of a map $\varepsilon:X\to{\mathcal{C}}_{0}$, together with an action map $\xi:X\times_{{\mathcal{C}}_{0}}{\mathcal{C}}_{1}\to X.$
Definition 0.2.2. A monad $J$ is Cartesian if it satisfies the following properties: (1) $J$ preserves pullbacks. (2) The naturality diagrams for the product $\mu:J^{2}\to J$ and the unit $\eta:{\mathop{\textnormal{id}}\nolimits}\to J$ are all pullbacks.
Definition 11. Let $f:\mathcal{P}\to\mathcal{Q}$ be a morphism in $\mathbf{sProp}$ or $\mathbf{sProperad}$. We say that $f$ is a weak equivalence if W1: for each input-output profile $\binom{\underline{b}}{\underline{a}}$ in $\operatorname{Col}(\mathcal{P})$ the morphism $f:\mathcal{P}\binom{\underline{b}}{\underline{a}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{Q}% \binom{f\underline{b}}{f\underline{a}}$ is a weak homotopy equivalence of simplicial sets; and W2: the functor $\pi_{0}f:\pi_{0}\mathcal{P}\rightarrow\pi_{0}\mathcal{Q}$ is an equivalence of categories. We say that the morphism $f$ is a fibration if F1: for each input-output profile $\binom{\underline{b}}{\underline{a}}$ in $\operatorname{Col}(\mathcal{P})$ the morphism $f:\mathcal{P}\binom{\underline{b}}{\underline{a}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{Q}% \binom{f\underline{b}}{f\underline{a}}$ is a Kan fibration of simplicial sets; and F2: the functor $\pi_{0}f:\pi_{0}\mathcal{P}\rightarrow\pi_{0}\mathcal{Q}$ is an isofibration. Let $\mathcal{W}_{c}$ (resp. $\mathcal{F}_{c}$) be the weak equivalences (resp. fibrations) in $\mathbf{sProperad}$, and $\mathcal{W}$ (resp. $\mathcal{F}$) be the weak equivalences (resp. fibrations) in $\mathbf{sProp}$.
Definition 16. The set $I$ consists of the following morphisms of simplicial properads: C1: For $n,m,p\geq 0$, the maps $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}[\partial\Delta[p]]\to\mathcal{G}_{n,m}[\Delta[p]]$. C2: The $\mathbf{sSet}$-functor $\varnothing\hookrightarrow\mathcal{I}$ viewed as a morphism of simplicial properads. The set $J$ of consists of the following morphisms of simplicial properads: A1: For $n,m,p\geq 0$ and $0\leq k\leq p$, the maps $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}[\Lambda[k,p]]\to\mathcal{G}_{n,m}[\Delta[p]]$. A2: The $\mathbf{sSet}$-functors $\mathcal{I}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{H}$ for $\mathcal{H}\in\mathbf{H}$ which take $x$ to $x$, viewed as morphisms of simplicial properads.
Definition 15. For $n,m\geq 0$, let $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}:\mathbf{sSet}\to\mathbf{sProperad}$ be the functor characterized by the property that $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{sProperad}}(\mathcal{G}_{n,m}[X],\mathcal{P})=% \left\{(\underline{c};\underline{d}),f:|\underline{c}|=n,|\underline{d}|=m,f% \in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{sSet}}\left(X,\mathcal{P}\binom{\underline{d}}{% \underline{c}}\right)\right\}.$
Definition 9. A model category $\mathcal{C}$ is cofibrantly generated if there are sets $I$ and $J$ of maps such that • The domains of $I$ are small relative to $I\text{-cell}$; • The domains of $J$ are small relative to $J\text{-cell}$; • The class of fibrations is $J\text{-inj}$; and • The class of acyclic fibrations is $I\text{-inj}$.
Definition 3.4. A Reedy fibrant simplicial $G$-space is a Segal $G$-space if the Segal maps are $G$-equivalences for all $n\geq 2$.
Definition 3.1. Let $G$ be a group. A simplicial $G$-space is a functor ${\bf\Delta}^{op}\rightarrow G\mathcal{T}op$.
Definition 2.1. A category $\mathcal{C}$ is topological if it is enriched in the category $\mathcal{T}op$, i.e., if for any objects $X$ and $Y$ of $\mathcal{C}$, there is a space $\text{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ together with an associative, continuous composition.
Definition 2.2. A model category $\mathcal{M}$ is a topological model category if it is a topological category satisfying the following conditions. (1) The category $\mathcal{M}$ is tensored and cotensored over $\mathcal{T}op$, so that, given any objects $X$ and $Y$ of $\mathcal{M}$ and topological space $A$, there is an object $X\otimes A$ of $\mathcal{M}$ and a topological space $Y^{A}$ such that there are natural homeomorphisms $\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(X\otimes A,Y)\cong\text{Map}_{\mathcal{T}op}(A,\text{% Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(X,Y))\cong\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(X,Y^{A}).$ (2) If $i\colon A\rightarrow B$ is a cofibration and $p\colon X\rightarrow Y$ is a fibration in $\mathcal{M}$, then the induced map of topological spaces $\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(i^{*},p_{*})\colon\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(B,X)% \rightarrow\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(A,X)\times_{\text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(A,Y)}% \text{Map}_{\mathcal{M}}(B,Y)$ is a fibration which is a weak equivalence if either $i$ or $p$ is.
Definition 3.3. Let $X$ be a simplicial $G$-space. For any $n\geq 2$, the Segal map is $\varphi_{n}\colon X_{n}\rightarrow\underbrace{X_{1}\times_{X_{0}}\cdots\times_% {X_{0}}X_{1}}_{n}$ induced by all the maps $X(\alpha_{i})$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$ and $\mathcal{A}^{\prime\prime}$ be additive categories. The diagram $\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\xymatrix@C=2.7pc{\mathcal{A% }^{\prime}\ar[r]^{i_{*}}&\mathcal{A}\ar@<+2.8ex>[l]_{i^{!}}\ar@<-2.8ex>[l]_{i^% {*}}\ar[r]^{j^{*}}&\mathcal{A}^{\prime\prime}\ar@<+2.8ex>[l]_{j_{*}}\ar@<-2.8% ex>[l]_{j_{!}}}\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad(2.1)$ of additive functors is a recollement of additive category $\mathcal{A}$ relative to additive categories $\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$ and $\mathcal{A}^{\prime\prime}$, if the following conditions are satisfied: (R1) $(i^{*},i_{*}),(i_{*},i^{!}),(j_{!},j^{*})$ and $(j^{*},j_{*})$ are adjoint pairs; (R2) $i_{*},j_{!}$ and $j_{*}$ are full embeddings; (R3) Im$i_{*}$=Ker$j^{*}$.
Definition 3.1. (cf.[7],[11]) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a triangulated category, and $\mathcal{D}\subseteq\mathcal{Z}$ be subcategories of $\mathcal{C}$. Then the pair $(\mathcal{Z},\mathcal{Z})$ is called a $\mathcal{D}$-$mutation\ pair$ if the following conditions are satisfied. (1) For any object $X\in\mathcal{Z}$, there exists a triangle $\xymatrix@C=0.5cm{X\ar[r]^{f}&D\ar[r]^{g}&Y\ar[r]^{h}&TX}$ where $Y\in\mathcal{Z}$, $D\in\mathcal{D}$, $f$ is a left $\mathcal{D}$-approximation and $g$ is a right $\mathcal{D}$-approximation. (2) For any object $Y\in\mathcal{Z}$, there exists a triangle $\xymatrix@C=0.5cm{X\ar[r]^{f}&D\ar[r]^{g}&Y\ar[r]^{h}&TX}$ where $X\in\mathcal{Z}$, $D\in\mathcal{D}$, $f$ is a left $\mathcal{D}$-approximation and $g$ is a right $\mathcal{D}$-approximation.
Definition 2.2. Let $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$ be a 1-cell in $\mathbb{S}$. Define a functor $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}\colon{}_{H}\mathit{set}/Y\to{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X$ as follows. (1) For $(B,\mathfrak{b})=(B\overset{\mathfrak{b}}{\to}Y)\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{H}\mathit{% set}/Y)$, define $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}(B,\mathfrak{b})=(X\underset{Y}{\times}B\overset% {p_{X}}{\longrightarrow}X)$ by the following. (i) $X\underset{Y}{\times}B=\{(x,b)\mid\alpha(x)=\mathfrak{b}(b)\}$ is the usual fibered product of sets. (ii) $G$-action on $X\underset{Y}{\times}B$ is given by $g(x,b)=(gx,\theta_{x}(g)b)\quad(\forall g\in G,(x,b)\in X\underset{Y}{\times}B).$ (iii) $p_{X}\colon X\underset{Y}{\times}B\to X$ is the projection onto $X$, which is obviously $G$-equivariant. (2) For a morphism $f\colon(B,\mathfrak{b})\to(B^{\prime},\mathfrak{b}^{\prime})$ in ${}_{H}\mathit{set}/Y$, define $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}(f)$ by $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}(f)\colon X\underset{Y}{\times}B\to X\underset{Y% }{\times}B^{\prime}\ ;\ (x,b)\mapsto(x,f(b)).$
Definition 1.6. Let $\iota\colon H\hookrightarrow G$ be a monomorphism of groups. For any $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{H}\mathit{set})$, we define $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$ by $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X=G\underset{H}{\times}X=(G\times X)/\sim,$ where the equivalence relation $\sim$ is defined by - $(\xi,x)$ and $(\xi^{\prime},x^{\prime})$ in $G\times X$ are equivalent if there exists $h\in H$ satisfying $\xi=\xi^{\prime}\iota(h),\ \ x^{\prime}=hx.$ We denote the equivalence class of $(\xi,x)$ by $[\xi,x]\in\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$. The $G$-action on $\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$ is defined by $g[\xi,x]=[g\xi,x]$ for any $g\in G$ and $[\xi,x]\in\mathrm{Ind}_{\iota}X$.
Definition 7.4. For a 1-cell $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$ and an object $(A,\mathfrak{a})\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set}/X)$, take $\displaystyle(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})_{\bullet}(A,\mathfrak{a})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(P\overset{\pi_{Y}}{\longrightarrow}Y),$ $\displaystyle(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})_{\bullet}(A% ,\mathfrak{a})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(X\underset{Y}{\times}P\overset{p_{X}}{\longrightarrow}X).$ Then the unit of the adjoint $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}\dashv(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})_{\bullet}$ gives a morphism $\zeta\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X((\frac{\alpha}{\theta})^{\ast}\ (\frac{\alpha}{% \theta})_{\bullet}(A,\mathfrak{a}),(A,\mathfrak{a})).$ Together with Proposition 2.4, we obtain a commutative diagram in $\mathbb{S}$ $\xy(-18,8)*+{\frac{X}{G}}="0";(-3,8)*+{\frac{A}{G}}="2";(18,8)*+{\frac{X% \underset{Y}{\times}P}{G}}="4";(-18,-8)*+{\frac{Y}{H}}="10";(18,-8)*+{\frac{P}% {H}}="14";{\ar_{\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G}}"2";"0"};{\ar_{(}0.52){\frac{\zeta}{G}}% "4";"2"};{\ar_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}"0";"10"};{\ar^{\frac{\alpha^{\diamond}}{% \theta^{\diamond}}}"4";"14"};{\ar^{\frac{\pi_{Y}}{H}}"14";"10"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"14"};\endxy$ whose outer square is a 2-fibered product. In this article, we call $(\ref{DiagPartialExp})$ the partial exponential diagram in $\mathbb{S}$, associated to $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}$ and $\mathfrak{a}$. The term partial means that, contrary to the case of ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$, 1-cells $\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G}$ appearing in $(\ref{DiagPartialExp})$ is restricted to equivariant ones.
Definition 4.2. Let $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$ be a 1-cell in $\mathbb{S}$, and let $(A,\mathfrak{a})=(A\overset{\mathfrak{a}}{\to}X)$ be an object in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}/X$. At a point $a\in A$, we consider the following equivalence relation $\underset{(\frac{\alpha}{\theta},\mathfrak{a})}{\equiv}$ on $G$. - Two elements $g,g^{\prime}\in G$ are said to satisfy $g\underset{(\frac{\alpha}{\theta},\mathfrak{a})}{\equiv}g^{\prime}$ at $a$, if they satisfy $\theta_{\mathfrak{a}(a)}(g)=\theta_{\mathfrak{a}(a)}(g^{\prime})$ and $g\mathfrak{a}(a)=g^{\prime}\mathfrak{a}(a)$.
Definition 1.12. A 1-cell $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$ is called stab-surjective, if the following conditions are satisfied. (i) $Y=H\alpha(X)$ holds. (ii) If $x,x^{\prime}\in X$ and $h,h^{\prime}\in H$ satisfy $h\alpha(x)=h^{\prime}\alpha(x^{\prime})$, then there exists $g\in G$ which satisfies $x^{\prime}=gx$ and $h=h^{\prime}\theta_{x}(g)$.
Definition 7.1. Let $G$ be a fixed finite group. For a morphism $f\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(X,Y)$ and an object $(A,\mathfrak{a})\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set}/X)$, take $\displaystyle f_{\bullet}(A,\mathfrak{a})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(\Pi_{f}(A)\overset{\pi_{Y}}{\longrightarrow}Y),$ $\displaystyle f^{\ast}f_{\bullet}(A,\mathfrak{a})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(X\underset{Y}{\times}\Pi_{f}(A)\overset{p_{X}}{\longrightarrow}X).$ Then the unit of the adjoint $f^{\ast}\dashv f_{\bullet}$ gives a morphism $\rho\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X(f^{\ast}f_{\bullet}(A,\mathfrak{a}),(A,\mathfrak{a% }))$. Thus we obtain a commutative diagram in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ $\xy(-18,8)*+{X}="0";(-3,8)*+{A}="2";(18,8)*+{X\underset{Y}{\times}\Pi_{f}(A)}=% "4";(-18,-8)*+{Y}="10";(18,-8)*+{\Pi_{f}(A)}="14";{\ar_{\mathfrak{a}}"2";"0"};% {\ar_{(}0.62){\rho}"4";"2"};{\ar_{f}"0";"10"};{\ar^{f^{\diamond}}"4";"14"};{% \ar^{\pi_{Y}}"14";"10"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"14"};\endxy$ whose outer square is a fibered product. Explicitly, the map $\rho$ is given by $\rho(x,(y,\sigma))=\sigma(x)\qquad(\forall(x,(y,\sigma))\in X\underset{Y}{% \times}\Pi_{f}(A)).$ A diagram in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ isomorphic to $(\ref{DiagExp})$ arising from some $f$ and $\mathfrak{a}$, is called an exponential diagram.
Definition 3.2. Let $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$ be an 1-cell. Define a functor $S_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X\to{}_{H}\mathit{set}/% \mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})$ as follows. From any morphism $f\colon(A,\mathfrak{a})\to(A^{\prime},\mathfrak{a}^{\prime})$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}/X$, we obtain a diagram in $\mathbb{S}$ $\xy(-22,20)*+{\frac{A}{G}}="0";(-22,-20)*+{\frac{A^{\prime}}{G}}="2";(-2,8)*+{% \frac{\mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G})}{H}}="4";% (4,18)*+{}="5";(-2,-8)*+{\frac{\mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\circ\frac{% \mathfrak{a}^{\prime}}{G})}{H}}="6";(4,-18)*+{}="7";(26,0)*+{\frac{\mathrm{SIm% }(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})}{H}}="8";(-8,0)*+{}="9";(48,0)*+{\frac{Y}{H}}="10";(5% .7,20)*+{}="11";(5.7,-20)*+{}="12";(28,12)*+{}="21";(28,-12)*+{}="22";{\ar^{% \frac{\upsilon_{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a})}}{\theta^{\prime}}}"0";"4"};{\ar_{% \frac{\upsilon_{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a}^{\prime})}}{\theta^{\prime\prime}}}"2% ";"6"};{\ar_{\frac{f}{G}}"0";"2"};{\ar^{\frac{\overline{\mathfrak{a}}}{H}}"4";% "8"};{\ar_{\frac{\overline{\mathfrak{a}}^{\prime}}{H}}"6";"8"};{\ar_{\frac{% \overline{f}}{H}}"4";"6"};{\ar^{\frac{\widetilde{\alpha}}{H}}"8";"10"};{\ar@/^% {1}.8pc/^{\frac{\upsilon_{\alpha}}{\theta}\circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G}}"0";"8"}% ;{\ar@/_{1}.8pc/_{\frac{\upsilon_{\alpha}}{\theta}\circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}^{% \prime}}{G}}"2";"8"};{\ar@/^{1}.8pc/|!{"8";"11"}\hole^{\frac{\widetilde{(% \alpha\circ\mathfrak{a})}}{H}}"4";"10"};{\ar@/_{1}.8pc/|!{"8";"12"}\hole_{% \frac{\widetilde{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a}^{\prime})}}{H}}"6";"10"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright(-17,0);(-13,0)};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"4";"5"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"6";"7"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"8";"9"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"8";"21"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"8";"22"};\endxy$ where $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G}=\frac{\widetilde{(\alpha\circ% \mathfrak{a})}}{H}\circ\frac{\upsilon_{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a})}}{\theta^{% \prime}}\quad\text{and}\quad\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}^{% \prime}}{G}=\frac{\widetilde{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a}^{\prime})}}{H}\circ\frac% {\upsilon_{(\alpha\circ\mathfrak{a}^{\prime})}}{\theta^{\prime\prime}}$ are $\mathrm{SIm}$-factorizations, and $\overline{\mathfrak{a}},\overline{\mathfrak{a}}^{\prime},\overline{f}$ are given by $\displaystyle\overline{\mathfrak{a}}\colon H\underset{G}{\times}A\to H% \underset{G}{\times}X\ ;\ [\eta,a]\mapsto[\eta,\mathfrak{a}(a)],$ $\displaystyle\overline{\mathfrak{a}}^{\prime}\colon H\underset{G}{\times}A^{% \prime}\to H\underset{G}{\times}X\ ;\ [\eta,a^{\prime}]\mapsto[\eta,\mathfrak{% a}^{\prime}(a^{\prime})],$ $\displaystyle\overline{f}\colon H\underset{G}{\times}A\to H\underset{G}{\times% }A^{\prime}\ ;\ [\eta,a]\mapsto[\eta,f(a)].$ Using this, we define $S_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}$ by $S_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}(A,\mathfrak{a})=(\mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta}% \circ\frac{\mathfrak{a}}{G})\overset{\overline{\mathfrak{a}}}{\longrightarrow}% \mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})),\qquad S_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}(f)=% \overline{f}$ for any object $(A,\mathfrak{a})$ and morphism $f$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}/X$.
Definition 7.8. A map $\varphi\colon A\to B$ between additive monoids $A$ and $B$ is said to be polynomial of degree $n$ if $\kappa_{B}\circ\varphi\colon A\to K_{0}B$ is polynomial of degree $n$ in the sense of Definition 7.7, where $\kappa_{B}\colon B\to K_{0}B$ is the group completion map.
Definition 4.6. For any 1-cell $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$, take its $\mathrm{SIm}$-factorization $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}=\frac{\widetilde{\alpha}}{H}\circ\frac{\upsilon_{\alpha}% }{\theta}$, and define a functor $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})_{\bullet}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X\to{}_{H}\mathit{% set}/Y$ to be the composition of the following sequence of functors. ${}_{G}\mathit{set}/X\overset{(-)^{\theta}}{\longrightarrow}{}_{G}\mathit{set}/% X\overset{S_{\theta}}{\longrightarrow}{}_{H}\mathit{set}/\mathrm{SIm}(\frac{% \alpha}{\theta})\overset{\Pi_{\widetilde{\alpha}}}{\longrightarrow}{}_{H}% \mathit{set}/Y$
Definition 1.9. Let $\mathbb{C}$ be a strict 2-category with invertible 2-cells. For any 0-cells $A_{1},A_{2},B$ and 1-cells $f_{i}\colon A_{i}\to B\ (i=1,2)$, 2-fibered product of $f_{1}$ and $f_{2}$ is defined to be a quartet $(A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2},\pi_{1},\pi_{2},\kappa)$ as in the diagram $\xy(-9,6)*+{A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2}}="0";(9,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-9,-6)*+{A_{1}}="4";% (9,-6)*+{B}="6";{\ar^{(}0.6){\pi_{2}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{\pi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{% 2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{=>}_{\kappa}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy,$ which satisfies the following conditions. (i) For any diagram in $\mathbb{C}$ $\xy(-8,6)*+{X}="0";(8,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-8,-6)*+{A_{1}}="4";(8,-6)*+{B}="6";{% \ar^{g_{2}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{g_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";% "6"};{\ar@{=>}^{\varepsilon}(-2,0);(2,0)};\endxy,$ there exist $g,\xi_{1},\xi_{2}$ as in the diagram $\xy(-22,16)*+{X}="-2";(-8,6)*+{A_{1}\times_{B}A_{2}}="0";(8,6)*+{A_{2}}="2";(-% 8,-7)*+{A_{1}}="4";(8,-7)*+{B}="6";{\ar^{g}"-2";"0"};{\ar@/^{1}.24pc/^{g_{2}}"% -2";"2"};{\ar@/_{1}.24pc/_{(}0.68){g_{1}}"-2";"4"};{\ar_{(}0.66){\pi_{2}}"0";"% 2"};{\ar^{\pi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar^{f_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{f_{1}}"4";"6"};{\ar@{=>}% _{\kappa}(-1.5,-1);(2.5,-1)};{\ar@{=>}^{\xi_{1}}(-12,3);(-16,-1)};{\ar@{=>}_{% \xi_{2}}(-8,9);(-6,14)};\endxy,$ satisfying $\varepsilon\cdot(f_{1}\circ\xi_{1})=(f_{2}\circ\xi_{2})\cdot(\kappa\circ g)$, namely making the following diagram of 2-cells commutative. $\xy(-12,6)*+{f_{1}\circ\pi_{1}\circ g}="0";(12,6)*+{f_{2}\circ\pi_{2}\circ g}=% "2";(-12,-6)*+{f_{1}\circ g_{1}}="4";(12,-6)*+{f_{2}\circ g_{2}}="6";{\ar@{=>}% ^{\kappa\circ g}"0";"2"};{\ar@{=>}_{f_{1}\circ\xi_{1}}"0";"4"};{\ar@{=>}^{f_{2% }\circ\xi_{2}}"2";"6"};{\ar@{=>}_{\varepsilon}"4";"6"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$ (ii) For any triplets $(g,\xi_{1},\xi_{2})$ and $(g^{\prime},\xi_{1}^{\prime},\xi_{2}^{\prime})$ as in (i), there exists a unique 2-cell $\zeta\colon g\Rightarrow g^{\prime}$ which satisfies $\xi_{i}^{\prime}\cdot(\pi_{i}\circ\zeta)=\xi_{i}\ (i=1,2)$.
Definition 3.3. For any 1-cell $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}\colon\frac{X}{G}\to\frac{Y}{H}$, let $\frac{\alpha}{\theta}=\frac{\widetilde{\alpha}}{H}\circ\frac{\upsilon_{\alpha}% }{\theta}$ be its $\mathrm{SIm}$-factorization, and define a functor $(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})_{+}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}/X\to{}_{H}\mathit{set}/Y$ to be the composition of ${}_{G}\mathit{set}/X\overset{S_{\frac{\alpha}{\theta}}}{\longrightarrow}{}_{H}% \mathit{set}/\mathrm{SIm}(\frac{\alpha}{\theta})\overset{\widetilde{\alpha}_{+% }}{\longrightarrow}{}_{H}\mathit{set}/Y.$
